# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-authentication-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorassertionresponse] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorassertionresponse] It’s been available across browsers since September 2021.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorassertionresponse] The **`AuthenticatorAssertionResponse`** interface of the Web Authentication API contains a digital signature from the private key of a particular WebAuthn credential.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorassertionresponse] The relying party's server can verify this signature to authenticate a user, for example when they sign in.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorassertionresponse] An `AuthenticatorAssertionResponse` object instance is available in the `response` property of a `PublicKeyCredential` object returned by a successful `navigator.credentials.get()` call.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorassertionresponse] This interface inherits from `AuthenticatorResponse`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorassertionresponse] An `ArrayBuffer` containing information from the authenticator such as the Relying Party ID Hash (rpIdHash), a signature counter, test of user presence and user verification flags, and any extensions processed by the authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorassertionresponse] Contains the JSON-compatible serialization of the data passed from the browser to the authenticator in order to authenticate with this credential — i.e., when `CredentialsContainer.get()` is called with a `publicKey` option.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorassertionresponse] This data contains some information from the options passed into the `get()` call, and some information controlled by the browser.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorassertionresponse] An assertion signature over `AuthenticatorAssertionResponse.authenticatorData` and `AuthenticatorResponse.clientDataJSON`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorassertionresponse] The assertion signature is created with the private key of the key pair that was created during the originating `navigator.credentials.create()` call and verified using the public key of that same key pair.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorassertionresponse] An `ArrayBuffer` containing an opaque user identifier, specified as `user.id` in the options passed to the originating `navigator.credentials.create()` call.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorassertionresponse] See Retrieving a public key credential for a detailed example.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorattestationresponse] The **`AuthenticatorAttestationResponse`** interface of the Web Authentication API is the result of a WebAuthn credential registration.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorattestationresponse] It contains information about the credential that the server needs to perform WebAuthn assertions, such as its credential ID and public key.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorattestationresponse] An `AuthenticatorAttestationResponse` object instance is available in the `response` property of a `PublicKeyCredential` object returned by a successful `CredentialsContainer.create()` call.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorattestationresponse] An `ArrayBuffer` containing authenticator data and an attestation statement for a new key pair generated by the authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorattestationresponse] Inherited from `AuthenticatorResponse`, this property contains the JSON-compatible serialization of the data passed from the browser to the authenticator in order to generate this credential — i.e., when `CredentialsContainer.create()` is called with a `publicKey` option.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorattestationresponse] This data contains some information from the options passed into the `create()` call, and some information controlled by the browser.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorattestationresponse] Returns an `ArrayBuffer` containing the authenticator data contained within the `AuthenticatorAttestationResponse.attestationObject` property.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorattestationresponse] Returns an `ArrayBuffer` containing the DER `SubjectPublicKeyInfo` of the new credential (see Subject Public Key Info), or `null` if this is not available.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorattestationresponse] Returns a number that is equal to a COSE Algorithm Identifier, representing the cryptographic algorithm used for the new credential.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorattestationresponse] Returns an array of strings describing which transport methods (e.g., `usb`, `nfc`) are believed to be supported with the authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorattestationresponse] The array may be empty if the information is not available.
[src:web-authentication-deep/authenticatorattestationresponse] See Creating a public key credential for a detailed example.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] It’s been available across browsers since September 2019.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] The **`create()`** method of the `CredentialsContainer` interface creates a new credential, which can then be stored and later retrieved using the `navigator.credentials.get()` method.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] The retrieved credential can then be used by a website to authenticate a user.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] Note that the Federated Credential Management API (FedCM) supersedes the federated credential type.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] An object that contains options for the requested new `Credentials` object.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] An `AbortSignal` object instance that allows an ongoing `create()` operation to be aborted.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] An aborted operation may complete normally (generally if the abort was received after the operation finished) or reject with an `AbortError` `DOMException`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] Each of the following properties represents a *credential type* being created.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] A `FederatedCredentialInit` object containing requirements for creating a federated identify provider credential.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] A `PasswordCredentialInit` object containing requirements for creating a password credential.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] A `PublicKeyCredentialCreationOptions` object containing requirements for creating a public key credential.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] Causes the `create()` call to request that the user agent creates new credentials via an authenticator — either for registering a new account or for associating a new asymmetric key pair with an existing account.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] If no credential object can be created, the promise resolves with `null`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] In the case of a `PasswordCredential` creation request, `id`, `origin`, or `password` were not provided (empty).
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] This example creates a password credential from a `PasswordCredentialInit` object.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] This example creates a federated credential from a `FederatedCredentialInit` object.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] This example creates a public key credential from a `PublicKeyCredentialCreationOptions` object.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] The `create()` call, if successful, returns a promise that resolves with a `PublicKeyCredential` object instance, representing a public key credential that can later be used to authenticate a user via a WebAuthn `get()` call.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] Its `PublicKeyCredential.response` property contains an `AuthenticatorAttestationResponse` object providing access to several useful pieces of information including the authenticator data, public key, transport mechanisms, and more.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-create] Some of this data will need to be stored on the server for future authentication operations against this credential — for example the public key, the algorithm used, and the permissible transports.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] The **`get()`** method of the `CredentialsContainer` interface returns a `Promise` that fulfills with a single credential, which can then be used to authenticate a user to a website.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] The API always fulfills with a single credential or `null`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] If multiple credentials are available and user mediation is allowed, then the browser will ask the user to select a single credential.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] An object that contains options for the request.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] A string indicating how the user is involved in retrieving the credential.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] Discovered credentials are presented to the user in a non-modal dialog box along with an indication of the origin requesting credentials.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] In practice, this means autofilling available credentials; see Autofill UI for more details of how this is used.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] If credentials can be handed over for a given operation without user mediation, they will be, enabling automatic reauthentication without user mediation.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] If user mediation is required, then the user agent will ask the user to authenticate.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] This value is intended for situations where you have reasonable confidence that a user won't be surprised or confused at seeing a login dialog box — for example on a site that doesn't automatically log users in, when a user has just clicked a "Login/Signup" button.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] The user will always be asked to authenticate.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] This value is intended for situations where you want to force user authentication — for example if you want a user to reauthenticate when a sensitive operation is being performed (like confirming a credit card payment), or when switching users.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] The user will not be asked to authenticate.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] The user agent will automatically reauthenticate the user and log them in if possible.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] If consent is required, the promise will fulfill with `null`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] This value is intended for situations where you would want to automatically sign a user in upon visiting a web app if possible, but if not, you don't want to present them with a confusing login dialog box.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] Instead, you'd want to wait for them to explicitly click a "Login/Signup" button.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] An `AbortSignal` object instance that allows an ongoing `get()` operation to be aborted.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] An aborted operation may complete normally (generally if the abort was received after the operation finished) or reject with the signal's reason (which is an `AbortError` `DOMException` by default, or a custom value if one was provided when calling `abort()`).
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] This option asks the browser to retrieve a stored password as a `PasswordCredential` object.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] This option asks the browser to retrieve a federated identity credential as an `IdentityCredential` object, using the Federated Credential Management API.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] This option's value is an `IdentityCredentialRequestOptions` object containing details of the specific identity providers that the website wants to use.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] This option asks the browser to retrieve a federated identity credential as a `FederatedCredential` object.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] This interface is now superseded, and developers should prefer to use the `identity` option, if it is available.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] An array of strings representing the protocols of the requested credentials' federated identity providers (for example, `"openidconnect"`).
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] An array of strings representing the credentials' federated identity providers (for example `"https://www.facebook.com"` or `"https://accounts.google.com"`).
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] This option asks the browser to retrieve a one-time password (OTP) as an `OTPCredential` object.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] This option's value is an array of strings which may only contain the string value `"sms"`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] This option asks the browser to retrieve an assertion signed using the Web Authentication API as a `PublicKeyCredential`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] This option's value is a `PublicKeyCredentialRequestOptions` object.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] If a single credential cannot be unambiguously obtained, the promise resolves with `null`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] The request was aborted by a call to the `abort()` method of the `AbortController` associated with this method's `signal` option.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] Note that if the caller of `abort()` provided a `reason` argument, then `get()` will be rejected with the value of `reason`, instead of an `AbortController` exception.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] The request was automatically aborted due to a timeout set using `AbortSignal.timeout()`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] When requesting an `IdentityCredential`, the request to the ID assertion endpoint is unable to validate the authentication, and rejects with an error response containing information about the reason.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] In the latter case, there may be some delay in the rejection to avoid leaking the IdP login status to the RP.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] The calling domain is not a valid domain.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] Relying parties can call `get()` with the `identity` option to make a request for users to sign in to the relying party via an identity provider (IdP), using identity federation.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] Check out Federated Credential Management (FedCM) API for more details on how this works.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] This call will start off the sign-in flow described in FedCM sign-in flow.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] A successful `get()` call returns a promise that resolves with a `PublicKeyCredential` object instance, representing a public key credential previously created via a WebAuthn `create()` that has now been used to authenticate a user.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] Its `PublicKeyCredential.response` property contains an `AuthenticatorAssertionResponse` object providing access to several useful pieces of information including the authenticator data, signature, and user handle.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] Some of this data will need to be stored on the server — for example the `signature` to provide proof that authenticator possesses the genuine private key used to create the credential, and the `userHandle` to link the user with the credential, sign in attempt, and other data.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] See Authenticating a user for more information about how the overall flow works.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] The code below triggers the browser's permission flow when an SMS message arrives.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] If permission is granted, then the promise resolves with an `OTPCredential` object.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] The contained `code` value is then set as the value of an `<input>` form element, which is then submitted.
[src:web-authentication-deep/credentialscontainer-get] In this example, we use `AbortSignal.timeout()` to automatically abort the request if it takes longer than 10 seconds.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] The **FIDO** (**Fast IDentity Online**) **Alliance** is an open industry association launched in February 2013 whose stated mission is to develop and promote authentication standards that "help reduce the world’s over-reliance on passwords".
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] FIDO addresses the lack of interoperability among devices that use strong authentication and reduces the problems users face creating and remembering multiple usernames and passwords.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] The USB security token device may be used to authenticate using a simple password (e.g. four-digit PIN) or by pressing a button.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] The specifications emphasize a device-centric model.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] Authentication over an insecure channel happens using public-key cryptography.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] The user's device registers the user to a server by registering a public key.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] To authenticate the user, the device signs a challenge from the server using the private key that it holds.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] The keys on the device are unlocked by a local user gesture such as a biometric or pressing a button.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] FIDO provides two types of user experiences depending on which protocol is used.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] Both protocols define a common interface at the client for whatever local authentication method the user exercises.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] The following open specifications may be obtained from the FIDO web site.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] The U2F 1.0 Proposed Standard (October 9, 2014) was the starting point for the specification known as FIDO 2.0 Proposed Standard (September 4, 2015).
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] The latter was formally submitted to the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) on November 12, 2015.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] Subsequently, the first Working Draft of the W3C Web Authentication (WebAuthn) standard was published on May 31, 2016.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] The WebAuthn standard has been revised numerous times since then, becoming a W3C Recommendation on March 4, 2019.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] Meanwhile the U2F 1.2 Proposed Standard (July 11, 2017) became the starting point for the Client to Authenticator Protocol 2.0 Proposed Standard, which was published on September 27, 2017.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] FIDO CTAP 2.0 complements W3C WebAuthn, both of which are in scope for the *FIDO2 Project*.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] The FIDO2 Project is a joint effort between the FIDO Alliance and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) whose goal is to create strong authentication for the web.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] At its core, FIDO2 consists of the W3C Web Authentication (WebAuthn) standard and the FIDO Client to Authenticator Protocol 2 (CTAP2).
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] FIDO2 is based upon previous work done by the FIDO Alliance, in particular the Universal 2nd Factor (U2F) authentication standard.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] Taken together, WebAuthn and CTAP specify a standard authentication protocol where the protocol endpoints consist of a user-controlled cryptographic authenticator (such as a smartphone or a hardware security key) and a WebAuthn Relying Party (also called a FIDO2 server).
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] A web user agent (i.e., a web browser) together with a WebAuthn client form an intermediary between the authenticator and the relying party.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] A single WebAuthn client Device may support multiple WebAuthn clients.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] For example, a laptop may support multiple clients, one for each conforming user agent running on the laptop.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] A conforming user agent implements the WebAuthn JavaScript API.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] As its name implies, the Client to Authenticator Protocol (CTAP) enables a conforming cryptographic authenticator to interoperate with a WebAuthn client.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] The CTAP specification refers to two protocol versions called CTAP1/U2F and CTAP2.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] An authenticator that implements one of these protocols is typically referred to as a U2F authenticator or a FIDO2 authenticator, respectively.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] A FIDO2 authenticator that also implements the CTAP1/U2F protocol is backward compatible with U2F.
[src:web-authentication-deep/fido-alliance] The invention of using a smartphone as a cryptographic authenticator on a computer network is claimed in US patent 7,366,913 filed in 2002.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] The **`PublicKeyCredential`** interface provides information about a public key / private key pair, which is a credential for logging in to a service using an un-phishable and data-breach resistant asymmetric key pair instead of a password.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] It inherits from `Credential`, and is part of the Web Authentication API extension to the Credential Management API.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] A string that indicates the mechanism by which the WebAuthn implementation is attached to the authenticator at the time the associated `navigator.credentials.create()` or `navigator.credentials.get()` call completes.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] Inherited from `Credential` and overridden to be the base64url encoding of `PublicKeyCredential.rawId`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] An `ArrayBuffer` that holds the globally unique identifier for this `PublicKeyCredential`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] This identifier can be used to look up credentials for future calls to `navigator.credentials.get()`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] An instance of an `AuthenticatorResponse` object.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] It is either of type `AuthenticatorAttestationResponse` if the `PublicKeyCredential` was the results of a `navigator.credentials.create()` call, or of type `AuthenticatorAssertionResponse` if the `PublicKeyCredential` was the result of a `navigator.credentials.get()` call.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] Always set to `public-key` for `PublicKeyCredential` instances.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with an object that can be used to check whether or not particular WebAuthn capabilities and extensions are supported.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] Returns a `Promise` which resolves to `true` if conditional mediation is available.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] Returns a `Promise` which resolves to `true` if an authenticator bound to the platform is capable of *verifying* the user.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] Convenience method for deserializing server-sent credential registration data when registering a user with credentials.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] Convenience method for deserializing server-sent credential request data when authenticating a (registered) user.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] Signals to the authenticator all of the valid credential IDs that the relying party server still holds for a particular user.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] Signals to the authenticator that a particular user has updated their user name and/or display name.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] Signals to the authenticator that a credential ID was not recognized by the relying party server, for example because it was deleted.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] If any extensions were requested, this method will return the results of processing those extensions.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] Convenience method for creating a JSON string representation of a `PublicKeyCredential` for sending to the server when registering a user with credentials and authenticating a registered user.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] Here, we use `navigator.credentials.create()` to generate a new credential.
[src:web-authentication-deep/publickeycredential] Here, we fetch an existing credential from an authenticator, using `navigator.credentials.get()`.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] To use WebAuthn, users require a compatible authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The standard does not specify how to store the keys required for signing, so a variety of authenticator types can be used.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The most common authenticator type is a platform authenticator, which is built into the operating system of the device.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Common platform authenticators include Android, Apple Keychain and Windows Hello.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] These make use of hardware security features (such as TEE and TPM), and often sync credentials between devices for ease-of-use.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Another common authenticator type is a roaming authenticator, where a separate hardware device authenticates the user by connecting over USB, Bluetooth Low Energy, or near-field communications (NFC).
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Most smartphones can be used as roaming authenticators, and dedicated physical security keys are also used.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn is effectively backward compatible with FIDO Universal 2nd Factor (U2F) as they both use the CTAP protocol.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Password managers can also be used as an authenticator, often with cloud sync.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Where credentials sync is not viable or possible, WebAuthn Hybrid Transport can be used to access credentials stored on another authenticator such as a smartphone.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Like legacy U2F, WebAuthn is resistant to some phishing attacks as the authenticator only offers credentials that were registered on the same website.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] However, unlike U2F, WebAuthn can be implemented in a passwordless manner.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Moreover, a roaming hardware authenticator resists malware, since the keys are stored on a separate device, which prevents the malware from accessing them directly.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The WebAuthn Level 1 and 2 standards were published as W3C Recommendations on 4 March 2019 and 8 April 2021 respectively.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] A Level 3 specification is currently a *First Public Working Draft* (FPWD).
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn is a core component of the FIDO2 Project under the guidance of the FIDO Alliance.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] FIDO2 is the successor to FIDO Universal 2nd Factor (U2F).
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Whereas U2F only supports multi-factor mode, having been designed to strengthen existing username/password-based login flows, FIDO2 adds support for single-factor mode.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] In multi-factor mode, the authenticator is activated by a test of *user presence*, which usually consists of a simple button push; no password is required.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] In single-factor mode, the authenticator (*something you have*) performs *user verification*.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Regardless of mode, the authenticator never shares its secrets or biometric data with the website.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Moreover, a single user's secret or biometric works with all websites, as the authenticator selects the correct cryptographic key material to use for the service requesting authentication after user verification was completed successfully.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] A secret and biometric on the authenticator can be used together, similarly to how they would be used on a smartphone.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] For example, a fingerprint provides convenient access to user's smartphone, but occasionally fingerprint access fails, in which case user can use a PIN.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] When Apple first introduced passkeys to the public in 2022, they emphasized their first-party platform integrations.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] This, combined with the lack of clear communication from other industry leaders, led some to speculate that passkeys were proprietary to Apple, which was not the case.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] As browsers and websites began to implement WebAuthn, the inconsistent feature-sets resulted in a variety of understandings of what exactly counted as a passkey.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Some people assumed that a passkey required management by a platform authenticator, or needed synchronization using the cloud.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] A better definition is that a passkey is any WebAuthn credential managed by any WebAuthn authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] This definition covers most of what different vendors refer to and accept as *passkeys*.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn specifies how a claimant demonstrates possession and control of a FIDO2 authenticator to a verifier called the WebAuthn Relying Party.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The authentication process is mediated by an entity called the WebAuthn Client, which is little more than a conforming web browser.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Authenticator is a multi-factor cryptographic authenticator that uses public-key cryptography to sign an authentication assertion targeted at the WebAuthn Relying Party.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Assuming the authenticator uses either a facial recognition, fingerprint or PIN for user verification, the authenticator itself is *something you have* while the facial recognition and fingerprint (biometric) are *something you are* and the PIN is *something you know*.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] To initiate the WebAuthn authentication flow, the WebAuthn Relying Party indicates its intentions to the WebAuthn Client (i.e., the browser) via JavaScript.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The WebAuthn Client communicates with the authenticator using a JavaScript API implemented in the browser.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] A roaming authenticator conforms to the FIDO Client to Authenticator Protocol (CTAP), and connected over USB, Bluetooth Low Energy, or near-field communications (NFC).
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn does not strictly require a roaming hardware authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Alternatively, a software authenticator (e.g., implemented on a smartphone) or a platform authenticator (i.e., an authenticator implemented directly on the WebAuthn Client Device) may be used.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Relevant examples of platform authenticators include Windows Hello and the Android operating system.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn Hybrid Transport allows the WebAuthn Client to access credentials stored on another authenticator such as a smartphone, useful in certain situations where credential sync is not viable.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] There is a lingering misunderstanding among users that biometric data is transmitted over the network in the same manner as passwords, which is not the case.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] When the WebAuthn Relying Party receives the signed authentication assertion from the browser, the digital signature on the assertion is verified using a trusted public key for the user.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] To obtain a public key for the user, the WebAuthn Relying Party initiates a WebAuthn registration flow that is similar to the authentication flow illustrated above.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The primary difference is that the authenticator now signs an attestation statement with its attestation private key.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The signed attestation statement contains a copy of the public key that the WebAuthn Relying Party ultimately uses to verify a signed authentication assertion.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The attestation certificate contains metadata describing the authenticator itself.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The digital signature on the attestation statement is verified with the trusted attestation public key for that particular model of authenticator.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] How the WebAuthn Relying Party obtains its store of trusted attestation public keys is unspecified.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] One option is to use the FIDO metadata service.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The attestation type specified in the JavaScript determines the trust model.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] For instance, an attestation type called self-attestation may be desired, for which the trust model is essentially trust on first use.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The WebAuthn Level 1 standard was published as a W3C Recommendation by the Web Authentication Working Group on 4 March 2019.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn is supported by Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Apple Safari and Opera.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The desktop version of Google Chrome has supported WebAuthn since version 67.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Firefox, which had not fully supported the previous FIDO U2F standard, included and enabled WebAuthn in Firefox version 60, released on 9 May 2018.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] An early Windows Insider release of Microsoft Edge (Build 17682) implemented a version of WebAuthn that works with both Windows Hello as well as external security keys.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Existing FIDO U2F security keys are largely compatible with the WebAuthn standard, though WebAuthn added the ability to reference a unique per-account "user handle" identifier, which older authenticators are unable to store.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] One of the first FIDO2-compatible authenticators was the second-generation Security Key by Yubico, announced on 10 April 2018.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The first FIDO2-compatible authenticators with a display was Trezor Model T by SatoshiLabs, announced on 6 November 2019.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Trezor Model T was also the first authenticator that allowed users to select which FIDO2 resident credential should be used directly on a device.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The first Security Level 2 certified FIDO2 key, called "Goldengate" was announced one year later by eWBM on 8 April 2019.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Dropbox announced support for WebAuthn logins (as a 2nd factor) on 8 May 2018.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Apple announced that Face ID or Touch ID could be used as a WebAuthn platform authenticator with Safari on 24 June 2020.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Several password managers such as Bitwarden and Dashlane support WebAuthn.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] WebAuthn implements an extension of the W3C's more general Credential Management API, which is an attempt to formalize the interaction between websites and web browsers when exchanging user credentials.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The Web Authentication API extends the Credential Management `navigator.credentials.create()` and `navigator.credentials.get()` JavaScript methods so they accept a `publicKey` parameter.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] To check if a browser supports WebAuthn, scripts should check if the `window.PublicKeyCredential` interface is defined.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] In addition to `PublicKeyCredential`, the standard also defines the `AuthenticatorResponse`, `AuthenticatorAttestationResponse`, and `AuthenticatorAssertionResponse` interfaces in addition to a variety of dictionaries and other datatypes.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] The API does not allow direct access to or manipulation of private keys, beyond requesting their initial creation.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] In August 2018, Paragon Initiative Enterprises conducted a security audit of the WebAuthn standard.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] While they could not find any specific exploits, they revealed some serious weaknesses in the way the underlying cryptography is used and mandated by the standard.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Paragon Initiative Enterprises also criticized how the standard was initially developed, as the proposal was not made public in advance and experienced cryptographers were not asked for suggestions and feedback.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Hence the standard was not subject to broad cryptographic research from the academic world.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Despite these shortcomings, Paragon Initiative Enterprises still encourage users to continue to use WebAuthn but have come up with some recommendations for potential implementers and developers of the standard that they hope can be implemented before the standard is finalized.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Avoiding such mistakes as early as possible would protect the industry from any challenges that are introduced by broken standards and the need for backwards compatibility.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] ECDAA was only designed to use in combination with device attestation.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] This particular feature of WebAuthn is not necessarily required for authentication to work.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Current implementations allow the user to decide whether an attestation statement is sent during the registration ceremony.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] Independently, relying parties can choose to require attestation or not.
[src:web-authentication-deep/webauthn] ECDAA was removed from WebAuthn Level 2 as it was not implemented by browsers nor relying parties.
